                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.00111 Armament Control/215: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Ethiopia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-18T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 18, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>78. Your No. 135, October 18, 11 a.m. Section 1 of the Neutrality Act, pursuant
                    to which the President issued his Proclamation prohibiting the exportation of
                    arms to Italy and Ethiopia, is so worded that the President has no authority to
                    permit exceptions. In these circumstances, the Department has been obliged to
                    inform the Ethiopian Consul General and other interested persons that the
                    exportation of the airplanes intended for the use of the Ethiopian Red Cross
                    would be definitely contrary to law.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
